The Manlius to whom this elegy is addressed is the same person for whom Catullus composed the beautiful epithalamium (LXI.) on the occasion of the marriage of ¹ Manlius with Julia’ That he was a member of the noble house of the Manlii Torquati there is no doubt, but nothing more can be told of him. The intimacy of the poet with his friend or patron is beautifully and clearly expressed. The elegy is an answer to a letter oi Manlius desiring Catullus to console him in some sudden and severe afflicticn, and the poet replies that although gratitude and affection prompt him to comply with the nequest, he can respond to it imperfectly, since he himself also is orerwhelmed with grief on account of the recent death of his brother.
